{"accepted":[{"assertion":"Formal-Conjectures statement: Erdos1002.erdos_1002 https://google-deepmind.github.io/formal-conjectures/theorem/?name=Erdos1002.erdos_1002.","id":"vf_6cdf777af544a4c6","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"},{"assertion":"Erdős Problem #1002: declared status 'open'. Formalized: yes. For any $0<\\alpha<1$, let\\[f(\\alpha,n)=\\frac{1}{\\log n}\\sum_{1\\leq k\\leq n}(\\tfrac{1}{2}-\\{ \\alpha k\\}).\\]Does $f(\\alpha,n)$ have an asymptotic distribution function?\n\nIn other words, is there a non-decreasing function $g$ such that $g(-\\infty)=0$, $g(\\infty)=1$,\nand\\[\\lim_{n\\to \\infty}\\lvert \\{ \\alpha\\in (0,1): f(\\alpha,n)\\leq c\\}\\rvert=g(c)?\\] Current best: Kesten \\cite{Ke60} proved that if\\[f(\\alpha,\\beta,n)=\\frac{1}{\\log n}\\sum_{1\\leq k\\leq n}(\\tfrac{1}{2}-\\{\\beta+\\alpha k\\})\\]then $f(\\alpha,\\beta,n)$ has asymptotic distribution function\\[g(c)=\\frac{1}{\\pi}\\int_{-\\infty}^{\\rho c}\\frac{1}{1+t^2}\\mathrm{d}t,\\]where $\\rho>0$ is an explicit constant. Prize: no. Tags: analysis, diophantine approximation.","id":"vf_c5b516ef04ab81bd","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"}],"accepted_activity":false,"activity":[],"activity_types":[],"attempt_count":0,"banked_attempt_count":0,"commits":[],"dependency_impact":"none","detail_url":"problems/1002.json","draft_proposals":[],"edges":[{"evidence":"Problem identity derived from the accepted finding's pinned source anchor.","inferred":true,"relation":"describes","source":"vf_6cdf777af544a4c6","source_root":"sha256:1faedc24f040a60a22177b456c74b969a61ce8836082297b1835797a57b4fa56","target":"erdos:1002","trust":"signed"},{"evidence":"Materialized typed link between accepted findings.","inferred":true,"relation":"synthesized_from","source":"vf_6cdf777af544a4c6","source_root":"sha256:1faedc24f040a60a22177b456c74b969a61ce8836082297b1835797a57b4fa56","target":"vf_c5b516ef04ab81bd","trust":"signed"},{"evidence":"Problem identity derived from the accepted finding's pinned sour